 worlds to dramatize new ways of approaching the politics of radical difference and the possibility of transforming reality. By exploring and constructing relations between James's pluralism and the ontological turn in anthropology, Savransky offers a new conceptualization of the pluriverse that fosters modes of thinking and living otherwise.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aPluralismxPolitical aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311074331908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2021 Englishz978311075418608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2021z9783110753967oZDB-23-DSL40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978147802143840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478021438423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478021438/original  a978-3-11-074331-9  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-075400-1  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishb2021  a978-3-11-075418-6  EBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2021 Englishb2021  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DSLb2021